    "R. Alan Culpepper": "Surprisingly, it makes no reference to Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 teaching or exorcisms. In\naddition, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` no longer frequents the synagogues; the last reference to\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` being in a synagogue in Mark is in 6:\nciples\u2019 lack of understanding (6:52) and the Pharisees\u2019 misplaced piety\n(7:1-15).\nResponding to the woman, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` announces that because of what she\nsaid the demon had gone out of her daughter. In Matthew, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019\nresponse is different, probably as a result of Matthean redaction:\n\u201cWoman, great is your faith! Let it be done for you as you wish\u201d (Matt\n[v_Mat_8_13] 15:28; cf. Matt 8:13). The reference to the girl\u2019s bed reminds the reader\nof the raising of Jairus\u2019s daughter (5:40-42) and the paralytic taking up\nhis pallet (2:11-12). There are three other Gospel accounts of healings\n[v_Mat_8_13] at a distance. All involve Gentiles. In Matthew 8:13 and John `[char_John_Ref]` 4:50,\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` sends the petitioner home with the command, \u201cGo\u201d (7:29). Each\nof the stories typically ends with praise of the faith of the Gentile peti-\n[v_Mat_8_10] tioner (Matt 8:10; 15:28; Luke 7:9). Mark leaves this element relatively\nunderstated and implicit. Nevertheless, the point is clear, and the\nSyrophoenician woman serves as yet another Markan minor character\nwhose persistent faith is ultimately rewarded.\nThis experience may have been a turning point for Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 ministry.\nWhereas he had worked only among the Jews before this incident (with\nthe notable exception of the exorcism of the Gadarene demoniac,\n5:1-20), this courageous and witty Gentile woman may have convinced\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` that God\u2019s mercy could not be limited to the Jews only. In the\nnext paragraph Mark reports Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 travel through the Decapolis, and at\nthe beginning of the next chapter Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` feeds a multitude of 4,000, just\nas earlier he had fed the 5,000, but this time the feeding takes place on\nthe other side of the Sea of Galilee, in a Gentile area. What Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` had\ndone for the Jewish crowd, he now did for the Gentile crowd\u2014he gave\nthem bread.\n242\n[v_Mrk_7_1] [v_Mrk_7_2] [v_Mrk_7_3] [v_Mrk_7_4] [v_Mrk_7_5] [v_Mrk_7_6] [v_Mrk_7_7] [v_Mrk_7_8] [v_Mrk_7_9] [v_Mrk_7_10] [v_Mrk_7_11] [v_Mrk_7_12] [v_Mrk_7_13] [v_Mrk_7_14] [v_Mrk_7_15] [v_Mrk_7_16] [v_Mrk_7_17] [v_Mrk_7_18] [v_Mrk_7_19] [v_Mrk_7_20] [v_Mrk_7_21] [v_Mrk_7_22] [v_Mrk_7_23] [v_Mrk_7_24] [v_Mrk_7_25] [v_Mrk_7_26] [v_Mrk_7_27] [v_Mrk_7_28] [v_Mrk_7_29] [v_Mrk_7_30] [v_Mrk_7_31] [v_Mrk_7_32] [v_Mrk_7_33] [v_Mrk_7_34] [v_Mrk_7_35] [v_Mrk_7_36] [v_Mrk_7_37] Mark 7:1-37\nThe Miracle of Hearing for the Deaf, 7:31-37\nThe account of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 healing of the deaf mute carries much more sig-\nnificance than one may see in it on first reading. It is strategically\nlocated following Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 conversation with the Syrophoenician woman\nand just before his feeding of the 4,\n000. Symbolically it announces that\nthrough Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` the ears of the Gentiles can be opened to hear the good\nnews of God and their tongues can be loosed to proclaim God\u2019s glory.\nThe story opens with a geographical notice, just as did the story of\n[v_Mrk_7_31] the Syrophoenician woman. Mark 7:31 therefore balances 7:24, as each\ncontains a reference to \u201cthe region of Tyre.\u201d The geographical references\nin"
